ilding. It has two large galleries to display antiques. Antiques found in Bagerhat are categorized into two parts. One of them are the earthen materials and another is wooden and slate (rock/stone). There is a photo gallery too to display the rare photos of artifacts and ruined architectural structures.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The building is built later but the designers made it with a beauty of ancient structure visibly similar with the mosque because of the dome so that the museum does not look odd in the complex. During the summer time, it is opened from 9 am to 6 pm for the visitors. The entry fee for the complex is 20 taka for Bangladeshi citizens and it is also the ticket of the museum, there is no separate ticket is needed.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><strong>How To Go There:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Route 1: From Bagerhat ride any bus going to Khulna or hire an auto and drop down in front of Shat Gonbuj Mosque.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Route 2: From Khulna – Goplaganj – Katakhali – Fakirhat – Mongla you don’t need to go to Bagerhat. On the way to Bagerhat, before bagerhat drop down in front of Shat Gonbuj Mosque.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style="color: #000080;"><strong>Kodhla Moth</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong><span style="color: #800000;"><img class="size-full wp-image-409 alignleft" src="http://localhost/travelguide/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/index5-1.jpg" alt="index5" width="259" height="194" />Kodla Math</span> </strong>Temple was built by a Brahman in the 17th century, but is not standing the test of time very well. It’s near a village named Ayodhya, about 10 km or so north of Bagerhat. This is a Hindu Moth (though it doesn’t look like a regular Hindu temple) locally known as Kodla Moth as it is located at the village Kodola. It has another name, which is Ojodhdhar Moth. May be the correct spelling can be Ayodhyar Moth. It is a tall structure that has a square shaped base. Approximate height of the Moth is slightly above the 18 meters.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><strong> </strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><strong>How To Go There:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">You can use a rented car during this traveling or the public transportation. You can hire a battery driven vehicles for the round trip. By using local transports reach at the Jatrapur Bazar first, and from there take another vehicle or van to reach at the Kodola Moth.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"></p>\r\n\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000080;"><strong>Bagerhat More Tourist Spot and Attraction:</strong></span></h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><em>Khan Jahan Ali Tomb</em></span></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><em>Singair Mosque</em></span></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><em>Khanjeli Dighi</em></span></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><em>Mongla Sea port</em></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong> </strong></p>', 'Bagerhat District', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '399-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-02-11 20:10:46', '2016-02-11 14:10:46', '', 399, 'http://localhost/travelguide/index.php/2016/02/11/399-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(411, 1, '2016-02-11 20:12:29', '2016-02-11 14:12:29', '<h2><span style="color: #000080;"><strong>Sundarban</strong></span></h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><img class=" wp-image-415 alignleft" src="http://localhost/travelguide/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/1-1.jpg" alt="1" width="269" height="179" /> <img class=" wp-image-416 alignleft" src="http://localhost/travelguide/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/2-300x144.jpg" alt="2" width="273" height="131" /> Satkhira region is mainly famous for the <span style="color: #800000;"><strong>Sundarbans</strong></span>. Sundarbans is most large single block of tidal mangrove forest in the world. It lies between the vast Bay of Bengal Ocean and rivers of the Ganges and the Brahmaputra, it spreads across <img class=" wp-image-417 alignleft" src="http://localhost/travelguide/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/3-2.jpg" alt="3" width="272" height="204" />Bangladesh and West Bengal in India. The waters of these rivers mix with the ocean water and so in this part of their flow the rivers are brackish or saline. Water covers the forest-islands twice a day during high tide.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">It is considered a World Heritage site by UNESCO. The forest is mostly popular for incredible plants and wildlife. Trees having roots can breathe directly from the air. There are numerous species and it is mostly famous for Royal Bengal tiger. The forest safeguards people of north from cyclones and tsunami waves. Previously, the islanders were allowed to go into the forest to collect firewood, honey, crab and fish but now these activities have been banned by the governments of both Bangladesh and West Bengal.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><strong>How to go there:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">It is (mainly) located in Satkhira district of Khulna divison. It is 66.4km away from Satkhira. After reaching in Satkhira, you can use local transports or private cars to reach Sundarbans.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000080;"><strong>Sathkhira Other Tourist Spot and Attractions:</strong></span></h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><em>Nolta Sarif</em></span></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><em>Historical Church</em></span></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><em>Shyamsundar Temple</em></span></li>\r\n	<li style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #800000;"><em>Mozaffar Garden &amp; Resort</em></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Sathkhira District', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'sathkhira-district', '', '', '2016-02-11 20:19:25', '2016-02-11 14:19:25', '', 0, 'http://localhost/travelguide/?page_id=411', 0, 'page', '', 0),
